input.content:
{
  "week": "Week 07",
  "dateRange": "17 November - 23 November",
  "topics": [
    {
      "id": "attribution-theory",
      "title": "Attribution Theory",
      "subtitle": "How We Explain Behavior",
      "summary": "Attribution theory explores how people explain the causes of behavior, both their own and others'. Three classic theories form the foundation: Heider's Naïve Scientist Theory, Jones & Davis's Correspondence Inference Theory, and Kelley's Covariation Theory.",
      "keyTakeaways": [
        "Attributions can be internal (dispositional) or external (situational), affecting how we interpret behavior.",
        "Heider proposed that people act as 'naïve scientists' who seek causal explanations for events.",
        "Kelley's Covariation Theory uses consensus, distinctiveness, and consistency to determine attributions.",
        "Attribution biases like the Fundamental Attribution Error lead to systematic errors in judgment."
      ],
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "What is Attribution?"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "An attribution is an explanation for the causes of behavior, whether our own or others'. Psychologists distinguish between two main types of attributions:"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "title": "Types of Attributions",
          "items": [
            "Internal (Dispositional) Attribution: Behavior is explained by something inside the person, such as personality, intelligence, or motivation.",
            "External (Situational) Attribution: Behavior is explained by something outside the person, such as luck, task difficulty, or environmental factors."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Heider's Naïve Scientist Theory (1958)"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Fritz Heider proposed that people act as 'naïve scientists' who use rational processes to explain events in their social world. In the famous Heider and Simmel (1944) experiment, participants watched geometric shapes move around and attributed personality traits, intentions, and emotions to these inanimate objects—demonstrating our inherent drive to seek causal explanations."
        },
        {
          "type": "callout",
          "icon": "Info",
          "title": "Classic Study",
          "text": "When college students watched abstract geometric shapes moving in and out of a rectangle, they systematically interpreted the shapes as persons with specific personality traits, needs, and dispositions like aggression or fear, showing that we automatically seek causal explanations even for inanimate objects."
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Jones & Davis: Correspondence Inference Theory (1965)"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "This theory explains how we infer that a person's behavior corresponds to their underlying disposition or personality. Two key factors influence correspondent inferences:"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "title": "Factors in Correspondent Inference",
          "items": [
            "Intentionality: We are more likely to make dispositional attributions when behavior appears intentional rather than unintentional. The person must know the consequences and have the ability to perform the action.",
            "Social Desirability: We are more likely to attribute behavior to disposition when the effects are socially undesirable. For example, if someone is very rude in a social situation, we conclude they are an unpleasant person."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Kelley's Covariation Theory (1967, 1973)"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Harold Kelley proposed that when we have multiple observations of a person's behavior, we use three types of information to determine whether to make internal or external attributions:"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "title": "Three Dimensions of Covariation",
          "items": [
            "Consensus: Do other people behave the same way in response to this stimulus? High consensus = others act similarly; Low consensus = others act differently.",
            "Distinctiveness: Does the person behave this way in other situations? High distinctiveness = behavior is unique to this situation; Low distinctiveness = person behaves this way in most situations.",
            "Consistency: Does the person respond this way across time? High consistency = person always behaves this way; Low consistency = this is unusual behavior for this person."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "callout",
          "icon": "AlertCircle",
          "title": "Example: Sarah Fails Her PSYC100 Exam",
          "text": "Distinctiveness: High = failed only this exam; Low = failed other exams. Consistency: High = failed exams before; Low = rarely failed before. Consensus: High = other students failed this exam; Low = few others failed. High consensus + high distinctiveness + high consistency = External attribution (the exam was hard). Low consensus + low distinctiveness + high consistency = Internal attribution (Sarah lacks ability)."
        }
      ],
      "questions": [
        {
          "question": "According to Heider's Naïve Scientist Theory, what do people naturally seek when observing behavior?",
          "difficulty": "learning",
          "options": [
            "Emotional validation",
            "Causal explanations",
            "Social approval",
            "Behavioral predictions"
          ],
          "answer": "Causal explanations",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "Heider proposed that people act as naïve scientists who use rational processes to seek causal explanations for events, even attributing intentions to inanimate objects.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Emotional validation": "While people may seek emotional validation, Heider's theory specifically focuses on the cognitive process of seeking causal explanations.",
              "Social approval": "Social approval relates more to conformity and normative influence, not attribution processes.",
              "Behavioral predictions": "While predictions may follow from attributions, the theory emphasizes the search for causes, not predictions."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "In the Heider and Simmel (1944) study, participants watched geometric shapes move and attributed what to them?",
          "difficulty": "learning",
          "options": [
            "Physical properties only",
            "Random movements",
            "Personality traits and intentions",
            "Mathematical patterns"
          ],
          "answer": "Personality traits and intentions",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "Participants systematically interpreted the shapes as persons with personality traits, needs, and dispositions like aggression or fear, demonstrating our inherent drive to seek causal explanations.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Physical properties only": "Participants went beyond physical properties to attribute psychological characteristics to the shapes.",
              "Random movements": "Participants did not see the movements as random but as intentional and meaningful.",
              "Mathematical patterns": "The study focused on social-psychological interpretations, not mathematical analysis."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "According to Jones & Davis's Correspondence Inference Theory, when are we most likely to make dispositional attributions?",
          "difficulty": "application",
          "options": [
            "When behavior is unintentional and socially desirable",
            "When behavior is intentional and socially undesirable",
            "When behavior is unintentional and socially undesirable",
            "When behavior is intentional and socially desirable"
          ],
          "answer": "When behavior is intentional and socially undesirable",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "We are most likely to infer a correspondence between behavior and disposition when the behavior appears intentional AND when its effects are socially undesirable, as this reveals something unique about the person.",
            "incorrect": {
              "When behavior is unintentional and socially desirable": "Unintentional behavior does not allow us to infer much about disposition, and socially desirable behavior could be due to social norms.",
              "When behavior is unintentional and socially undesirable": "Unintentional behavior makes it difficult to infer dispositional causes regardless of social desirability.",
              "When behavior is intentional and socially desirable": "Socially desirable behavior could simply reflect conformity to norms rather than revealing underlying disposition."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "In Kelley's Covariation Theory, what does HIGH consensus indicate?",
          "difficulty": "learning",
          "options": [
            "The person behaves this way across different situations",
            "Other people behave the same way in this situation",
            "The person consistently behaves this way over time",
            "The behavior is socially desirable"
          ],
          "answer": "Other people behave the same way in this situation",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "High consensus means that other people respond similarly to the same stimulus or situation, suggesting the cause may be external (situational) rather than internal to the individual.",
            "incorrect": {
              "The person behaves this way across different situations": "This describes low distinctiveness, not consensus.",
              "The person consistently behaves this way over time": "This describes high consistency, not consensus.",
              "The behavior is socially desirable": "Social desirability is part of Jones & Davis's theory, not Kelley's covariation dimensions."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "Sarah fails her PSYC100 exam. If the failure shows HIGH consensus, HIGH distinctiveness, and HIGH consistency, what attribution would be made?",
          "difficulty": "application",
          "options": [
            "Internal attribution: Sarah lacks ability",
            "External attribution: The exam was difficult",
            "Internal attribution: Sarah didn't study",
            "External attribution: The professor grades unfairly"
          ],
          "answer": "External attribution: The exam was difficult",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "High consensus (others failed too) + high distinctiveness (Sarah only failed this exam) + high consistency (Sarah has failed similar exams before) leads to an external attribution—the exam was objectively difficult.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Internal attribution: Sarah lacks ability": "This would require LOW consensus (only Sarah failed), LOW distinctiveness (Sarah fails many exams), and HIGH consistency.",
              "Internal attribution: Sarah didn't study": "While possible, the high consensus and high distinctiveness pattern points more strongly to situational factors.",
              "External attribution: The professor grades unfairly": "While external, the specific pattern (high on all three dimensions) most directly suggests task difficulty."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "What does LOW distinctiveness indicate in Kelley's model?",
          "difficulty": "learning",
          "options": [
            "The person behaves this way in most situations",
            "Other people rarely behave this way",
            "The person rarely behaves this way",
            "The behavior is very distinctive"
          ],
          "answer": "The person behaves this way in most situations",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "Low distinctiveness means the behavior is typical across many situations for this person, suggesting an internal (dispositional) attribution rather than something specific to this situation.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Other people rarely behave this way": "This describes low consensus, not distinctiveness.",
              "The person rarely behaves this way": "This would be high distinctiveness, indicating the behavior is unique to this situation.",
              "The behavior is very distinctive": "This is the opposite—low distinctiveness means the behavior is NOT distinctive to this situation."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "A student always arrives late to all classes, not just psychology. Other students arrive on time, and the student has been late consistently all semester. What attribution is most appropriate?",
          "difficulty": "tricky",
          "options": [
            "External: The class schedule is inconvenient",
            "Internal: The student has poor time management",
            "External: The campus is difficult to navigate",
            "Internal: The student dislikes this professor"
          ],
          "answer": "Internal: The student has poor time management",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "This shows LOW consensus (others arrive on time), LOW distinctiveness (late to all classes), and HIGH consistency (always late). This pattern strongly suggests an internal attribution about the student's characteristics.",
            "incorrect": {
              "External: The class schedule is inconvenient": "If the schedule were the problem, we'd expect high consensus (others would also be late), which we don't see.",
              "External: The campus is difficult to navigate": "Again, if this were true, we'd expect high consensus (many students late), but only this student is consistently late.",
              "Internal: The student dislikes this professor": "The low distinctiveness (late to ALL classes) rules out this specific explanation—it's not about one professor."
            }
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "attribution-biases",
      "title": "Attribution Biases and Errors",
      "subtitle": "Systematic Mistakes in Social Judgment",
      "summary": "Despite our sophisticated attribution processes, people make systematic errors in judgment. Key biases include the Fundamental Attribution Error, False Consensus Effect, Self-Serving Bias, and Actor-Observer Effect.",
      "keyTakeaways": [
        "The Fundamental Attribution Error is the tendency to overemphasize dispositional factors and underemphasize situational factors when explaining others' behavior.",
        "The False Consensus Effect leads us to overestimate how much others agree with our views and behaviors.",
        "Self-Serving Bias causes us to take credit for success but blame external factors for failure.",
        "The Actor-Observer Effect describes how we attribute our own behavior to situations but others' behavior to dispositions."
      ],
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "The Fundamental Attribution Error (Ross, 1977)"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "The Fundamental Attribution Error (FAE) is the tendency to over-emphasize dispositional (personality-based) explanations for others' behavior while under-emphasizing situational influences. In other words, we tend to assume that what a person does reflects what 'kind' of person they are, rather than the social and environmental forces acting on them."
        },
        {
          "type": "callout",
          "icon": "Info",
          "title": "Ross, Amabile & Steinmetz (1977): The Quiz Game Study",
          "text": "Participants were randomly assigned to be questioners (who composed difficult questions) or contestants (who answered them). Despite knowing the roles were randomly assigned, both contestants and observers rated questioners as significantly more knowledgeable than contestants. This demonstrates the FAE: behavior was attributed to dispositional qualities (intelligence) rather than to the situational advantage (being able to choose the questions)."
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "In the Quiz Game Study, questioners were rated as having 67-83 points of general knowledge, while contestants were rated at only 41-51 points, despite the role assignment being entirely random. This shows how powerfully we overestimate dispositional factors and underestimate situational factors."
        },
        {
          "type": "callout",
          "icon": "AlertCircle",
          "title": "Jones & Harris (1967): Castro Study",
          "text": "Participants listened to pro- and anti-Fidel Castro speeches. Even when explicitly told the speech position was determined by a coin flip (not the speaker's choice), participants still rated those who gave pro-Castro speeches as having more positive attitudes toward Castro. This demonstrates the FAE persists even when situational constraints are made obvious."
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "False Consensus Effect (Ross et al., 1977)"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "The False Consensus Effect is our tendency to overestimate the degree to which others share our beliefs, values, and behaviors. We see our own choices as more typical than they actually are."
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "In Ross, Greene & House's (1977) study, participants were asked if they would wear a sign around campus. Those who agreed to wear the sign estimated that 63% of others would also agree (actual rate: 50%). Those who refused estimated only 23% would agree (actual rate: 50%). Both groups overestimated how many others would behave as they did."
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Self-Serving Bias (Miller & Ross, 1975)"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "The Self-Serving Bias is our tendency to take credit for success (self-enhancing bias) but deny responsibility for failure (self-protective bias). We make dispositional (internal) attributions for our successes and situational (external) attributions for our failures to protect and enhance self-esteem."
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Examples include saying 'I got 90 for my essay!' (internal attribution) versus 'The lecturer gave me 40!' (external attribution). This bias serves to maintain positive self-esteem."
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Actor-Observer Effect (Jones & Nisbett, 1972)"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "The Actor-Observer Effect describes how we attribute our own behavior to situational factors (when we are the actor) but attribute others' behavior to dispositional factors (when we are the observer)."
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "For example, when YOU give a bad presentation, you know it was because you had three other projects due, your computer crashed, etc. (situational). When SOMEONE ELSE gives a bad presentation, you assume they don't know the subject well, lack intelligence, or are terrible at public speaking (dispositional)."
        },
        {
          "type": "callout",
          "icon": "Info",
          "title": "Nisbett et al. (1973) Study",
          "text": "Male participants were asked 'Why did you choose your major?' and 'Why did your friend choose his major?' Actors (explaining their own choice) gave more situational reasons ('Engineering is a high-paying field'). Observers (explaining their friend's choice) gave more dispositional reasons ('My friend wants to make lots of money'). This shows the systematic actor-observer difference in attributions."
        }
      ],
      "questions": [
        {
          "question": "What is the Fundamental Attribution Error?",
          "difficulty": "learning",
          "options": [
            "Overemphasizing situational factors when explaining our own behavior",
            "Overemphasizing dispositional factors when explaining others' behavior",
            "Underestimating how much others agree with us",
            "Taking credit for success but blaming others for failure"
          ],
          "answer": "Overemphasizing dispositional factors when explaining others' behavior",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "The FAE is the tendency to over-emphasize dispositional (personality-based) explanations for others' behavior while under-emphasizing situational influences on that behavior.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Overemphasizing situational factors when explaining our own behavior": "This describes part of the Actor-Observer Effect, not the Fundamental Attribution Error.",
              "Underestimating how much others agree with us": "This is the opposite of the False Consensus Effect, which involves overestimating agreement.",
              "Taking credit for success but blaming others for failure": "This describes the Self-Serving Bias, not the Fundamental Attribution Error."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "In the Quiz Game Study (Ross et al., 1977), why did contestants and observers rate questioners as more knowledgeable?",
          "difficulty": "application",
          "options": [
            "Questioners were actually more intelligent",
            "They failed to account for the situational advantage of choosing questions",
            "Contestants wanted to protect their self-esteem",
            "Questioners studied more before the experiment"
          ],
          "answer": "They failed to account for the situational advantage of choosing questions",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "This demonstrates the Fundamental Attribution Error—participants attributed the questioners' performance to dispositional qualities (intelligence) rather than to the situational advantage of being able to select questions they knew answers to.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Questioners were actually more intelligent": "Roles were randomly assigned, so there was no actual intelligence difference—this is the mistaken attribution participants made.",
              "Contestants wanted to protect their self-esteem": "While contestants might have ego concerns, observers also made the same error, and the study measured ratings, not self-protection.",
              "Questioners studied more before the experiment": "There was no opportunity to study; the effect was due entirely to the situational role advantage."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "In the Castro Study (Jones & Harris, 1967), what did participants do even when told speech positions were determined by coin flip?",
          "difficulty": "tricky",
          "options": [
            "Correctly attributed speeches to chance",
            "Still rated pro-Castro speakers as having more positive attitudes toward Castro",
            "Refused to rate the speakers' attitudes",
            "Rated anti-Castro speakers as more intelligent"
          ],
          "answer": "Still rated pro-Castro speakers as having more positive attitudes toward Castro",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "Even when explicitly told the speech position was determined randomly by coin flip, participants still committed the FAE and attributed the speech content to the speakers' true attitudes, ignoring the situational constraint.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Correctly attributed speeches to chance": "This would be the rational response, but participants did NOT do this—they still made dispositional attributions despite knowing about the coin flip.",
              "Refused to rate the speakers' attitudes": "Participants completed the ratings as requested; they didn't refuse.",
              "Rated anti-Castro speakers as more intelligent": "Intelligence wasn't measured; the study focused on inferred attitudes toward Castro."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "What is the False Consensus Effect?",
          "difficulty": "learning",
          "options": [
            "Believing others always disagree with us",
            "Overestimating how much others share our beliefs and behaviors",
            "Underestimating our own abilities",
            "Attributing success to luck"
          ],
          "answer": "Overestimating how much others share our beliefs and behaviors",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "The False Consensus Effect is our tendency to see our own behavior and choices as more typical than they actually are, overestimating the degree to which others agree with us.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Believing others always disagree with us": "This is the opposite of the False Consensus Effect—we actually overestimate agreement, not disagreement.",
              "Underestimating our own abilities": "This relates more to self-esteem or self-efficacy issues, not the False Consensus Effect.",
              "Attributing success to luck": "This would be an external attribution and relates more to Self-Serving Bias (or lack thereof)."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "In Ross et al.'s (1977) sign-wearing study, what did participants who agreed to wear the sign estimate?",
          "difficulty": "application",
          "options": [
            "That 23% of others would also agree",
            "That 50% of others would also agree",
            "That 63% of others would also agree",
            "That 77% of others would also agree"
          ],
          "answer": "That 63% of others would also agree",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "Those who agreed to wear the sign estimated 63% of others would agree (actual rate: 50%), demonstrating the False Consensus Effect—they overestimated how many would behave as they did.",
            "incorrect": {
              "That 23% of others would also agree": "This was the estimate made by those who REFUSED to wear the sign, not those who agreed.",
              "That 50% of others would also agree": "This was the actual rate, not the overestimate made by those who agreed.",
              "That 77% of others would also agree": "This was the estimate made by those who REFUSED (thinking 77% would also refuse), not by those who agreed."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "The Self-Serving Bias involves making what types of attributions?",
          "difficulty": "learning",
          "options": [
            "Internal for failures, external for successes",
            "Internal for successes, external for failures",
            "External for both successes and failures",
            "Internal for both successes and failures"
          ],
          "answer": "Internal for successes, external for failures",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "The Self-Serving Bias leads us to take credit for success with internal attributions ('I got 90!') but deny responsibility for failure with external attributions ('The lecturer gave me 40!'). This protects and enhances self-esteem.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Internal for failures, external for successes": "This is the opposite of the Self-Serving Bias and would harm rather than protect self-esteem.",
              "External for both successes and failures": "This would show no bias; the Self-Serving Bias specifically involves different attributions for success vs. failure.",
              "Internal for both successes and failures": "This would be consistent but not self-serving; the bias involves differential attributions."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "According to the Actor-Observer Effect, when YOU give a bad presentation, you attribute it to _____, but when SOMEONE ELSE gives a bad presentation, you attribute it to _____.",
          "difficulty": "application",
          "options": [
            "Situational factors; situational factors",
            "Dispositional factors; dispositional factors",
            "Situational factors; dispositional factors",
            "Dispositional factors; situational factors"
          ],
          "answer": "Situational factors; dispositional factors",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "The Actor-Observer Effect means we attribute our own behavior (actor) to situational factors ('I had three projects due, my computer crashed') but others' behavior (observer) to dispositional factors ('They lack intelligence, poor public speaking skills').",
            "incorrect": {
              "Situational factors; situational factors": "This would show no actor-observer difference, but the effect specifically involves different attributions for self vs. others.",
              "Dispositional factors; dispositional factors": "This would be consistent but ignores the systematic difference between how we explain our own vs. others' behavior.",
              "Dispositional factors; situational factors": "This is the opposite of the Actor-Observer Effect—we are more generous with situational explanations for ourselves, not others."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "In Nisbett et al.'s (1973) study on major choice, actors gave _____ reasons for their own choice, while observers gave _____ reasons for their friend's choice.",
          "difficulty": "tricky",
          "options": [
            "Dispositional; situational",
            "Situational; dispositional",
            "Personal; personal",
            "External; external"
          ],
          "answer": "Situational; dispositional",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "Actors explaining their own major choice gave situational reasons ('Engineering is a high-paying field'), while observers explaining their friend's choice gave dispositional reasons ('My friend wants to make lots of money'). This demonstrates the Actor-Observer Effect.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Dispositional; situational": "This is the opposite of what was found—the Actor-Observer Effect predicts situational for self, dispositional for others.",
              "Personal; personal": "The key finding was the difference in attribution types, not similarity.",
              "External; external": "While 'external' is similar to 'situational,' the pattern was specifically situational for actors and dispositional for observers, not external for both."
            }
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "conformity-social-influence",
      "title": "Conformity and Social Influence",
      "subtitle": "How Groups Shape Our Behavior",
      "summary": "Conformity involves changing beliefs or behaviors to fit in with a group. Sherif's autokinetic effect study and Asch's line judgment experiments revealed different types of social influence: informational (desire to be correct) and normative (desire to be accepted).",
      "keyTakeaways": [
        "Conformity can involve internalization (genuine belief change) or compliance (public agreement without private acceptance).",
        "Sherif's study demonstrated informational social influence in ambiguous situations.",
        "Asch's line studies showed normative social influence and the power of group pressure even in unambiguous situations.",
        "Conformity increases with group size, decreases with dissenters, and varies by culture."
      ],
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Defining Conformity"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Conformity is a type of social influence involving a change in belief or behavior to fit in with a group. It can take two forms:"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "title": "Types of Conformity",
          "items": [
            "Internalization: Genuinely changing your real thoughts and feelings as a result of less direct pressure from others. Both public and private acceptance.",
            "Compliance: Agreeing with others' opinions and complying with their requests publicly, but not changing your real internal opinions. Public agreement without private acceptance."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Sherif's (1935) Autokinetic Effect Experiment"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Muzafer Sherif studied conformity using the autokinetic effect—when in total darkness, we perceive a small stationary bright light as moving (a perceptual illusion)."
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Participants first estimated how much the light moved when viewing it alone, then made estimates in groups of 2-3. Individual estimates converged toward a group norm. This demonstrates conformity in an ambiguous task where there is no objectively correct answer."
        },
        {
          "type": "callout",
          "icon": "Info",
          "title": "Informational Social Influence",
          "text": "Sherif's study demonstrates informational influence—we conform to information from others because it removes ambiguity and we desire to be correct. In ambiguous situations, we rely on others for information, leading to both public response and private acceptance (internalization)."
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Asch's (1950s) Line Judgment Experiments"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Solomon Asch investigated conformity in an unambiguous task where the correct answer was obvious. Participants judged which of three comparison lines matched a standard line in length."
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "title": "Asch's Procedure",
          "items": [
            "Control group: 35 out of 37 people (95%) correctly judged the matching line, showing the task was unambiguous.",
            "Experimental group: One real participant with 6-7 confederates (actors). Confederates were prearranged to give incorrect answers on certain trials.",
            "Results: 37% of responses given by real participants were incorrect, conforming to the group. Participants showed extreme discomfort and reported fear of social disapproval."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "callout",
          "icon": "AlertCircle",
          "title": "Normative Social Influence",
          "text": "Asch's study demonstrates normative influence—we conform to be liked and accepted, even when we privately know the group is wrong. The situation is not ambiguous, but we seek social approval, resulting in public compliance without private acceptance."
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Factors That Affect Conformity"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "title": "Key Factors",
          "items": [
